@SBK in TO

Tea is the most popular hot drink over here, more so than coffee. I've been drinking it all my life, mostly just dunking tea bags into mugs of hot water and not bothering about any details other than the quality of the tea itself (I mean, Lipton and supermarket brands are simply undrinkable - those brews taste like water flavored with dryer lint). And yet I can't relate at all to what you've been told.

What is "the bright taste of freshly boiled water"? It sounds like something from the cringey Facebook of some self-styled lifestyle guru. Maybe Francis the chemist could weigh in on this?

@Andrzej - Ew! No!

I buy my tea by the kilo -- in bulk, not in teabags. And I get the good stuff. 

I recommend Upton Tea, if you're interested. I assume there are similar importers in the EU.

@Andrzej
Water does have taste. I never buy bottled water but, having lived in NYC and spent time in dozens of cities, I can confirm that water from one city's system will differ from another's. Notoriously, Montreal bagels' excellence is attributed in  part to the water used to boil them.
And 'old' boiled water does acquire overtones from its container as well as from the process of being boiled. I've had plenty of tea made with urn water and even my untutored palate recognizes the ick factor that emerges in water after hours held captive in an urn.

